1
00:00:08,560 --> 00:00:09,560
Fancy a stroll?

2
00:00:10,320 --> 00:00:11,320
It's a lovely day.

3
00:00:12,560 --> 00:00:14,160
Stretch the legs,
breath of fresh air.

4
00:00:15,280 --> 00:00:16,320
I'm busy.

5
00:00:17,400 --> 00:00:19,080
I got a question for you,
Master Bruce.

6
00:00:20,840 --> 00:00:22,960
What if all of this

7
00:00:23,040 --> 00:00:25,720
was a complete and utter
bloody waste of time?

8
00:00:27,800 --> 00:00:29,880
What if you never discovered
who killed your mom and dad?

9
00:00:33,880 --> 00:00:37,000
What if you never get
to wreak revenge?

10
00:00:39,400 --> 00:00:40,400
I don't want revenge.

11
00:00:41,920 --> 00:00:43,600
I wanna understand how it all works.

12
00:00:44,200 --> 00:00:45,440
How Gotham works.

13
00:00:45,520 --> 00:00:48,960
Well, you'd have more chance
digging to China with a teaspoon.

14
00:00:49,040 --> 00:00:50,720
Take the Arkham project,
for instance.

15
00:00:51,480 --> 00:00:53,720
How did the Falcone and Maroni
crime families

16
00:00:53,800 --> 00:00:55,240
get such big shares in the deal?

17
00:00:55,880 --> 00:00:58,200
I mean, I know city hall is corrupt,

18
00:00:58,280 --> 00:01:01,240
but why didn't Wayne Enterprises
do something?

19
00:01:03,320 --> 00:01:04,920
Can you pass me that blue folder,
over there?

20
00:01:10,120 --> 00:01:12,880
Well, I suppose as hobbies go,
this is,

21
00:01:12,960 --> 00:01:15,600
a damn sight better than grilling
yourself like a bloody pork chop.

22
00:01:17,880 --> 00:01:20,480
Still, not particularly healthy,
is it?

23
00:01:20,560 --> 00:01:21,560
Thank you.

24
00:01:23,440 --> 00:01:24,440
Are you listening to me?

25
00:01:26,600 --> 00:01:28,560
Yeah, yeah, for sure.
I'll take a walk later.

26
00:01:28,640 --> 00:01:29,640
Thank you, Alfred.

27
00:01:36,800 --> 00:01:40,120
I won a piece of Arkham.
I strong-armed the mayor,

28
00:01:40,200 --> 00:01:41,760
I made Falcone back down,

29
00:01:41,840 --> 00:01:45,320
and you're telling me
that I can't rob a lousy casino?

30
00:01:45,400 --> 00:01:48,600
Sal, the casino is Falcone's
pride and joy.

31
00:01:48,680 --> 00:01:49,840
I mean, what's the point?

32
00:01:49,920 --> 00:01:52,080
For a few thousand bucks,
why mess with Falcone?

33
00:01:52,160 --> 00:01:53,360
That's the point,

34
00:01:54,080 --> 00:01:55,520
messing with Falcone.

35
00:01:55,600 --> 00:01:57,840
I want him and his people to know
we're not backing off.

36
00:01:57,920 --> 00:01:59,120
Arkham was only the beginning.

37
00:01:59,960 --> 00:02:02,840
We're taking over, Frankie.
Inch by inch.

38
00:02:02,920 --> 00:02:04,640
- Yeah, okay, but...
- "But, but, but."

39
00:02:05,760 --> 00:02:07,560
- Make it happen.
- Okay, boss.

40
00:02:16,160 --> 00:02:19,080
What are you looking at?
You got something to say?

41
00:02:19,160 --> 00:02:21,000
No, sir. Nothing at all.

42
00:03:00,960 --> 00:03:01,960
Hey.

43
00:03:02,760 --> 00:03:03,760
Hey, man!

44
00:04:05,240 --> 00:04:06,240
Hey.

45
00:04:08,120 --> 00:04:09,680
Hey, you gotta pay for that.

46
00:04:12,680 --> 00:04:14,880
Do not vex me, mortal.

47
00:04:17,200 --> 00:04:18,200
Yeah?

48
00:04:19,960 --> 00:04:21,640
Suit yourself, Zeus.

49
00:04:33,920 --> 00:04:36,560
Hey, it might look like the heel
of a hobo's shoe.

50
00:04:36,640 --> 00:04:37,760
Best burgers in midtown.

51
00:04:37,840 --> 00:04:39,480
- Huh, Efram?
- If you say so.

52
00:04:39,560 --> 00:04:42,480
All right. I want two cheeseburgers,
hold the sauce,

53
00:04:42,560 --> 00:04:44,240
extra pickles, two malted shakes.

54
00:04:44,320 --> 00:04:47,320
- No pickles on mine, please.
- Oh, you gotta trust me on this one.

55
00:04:47,400 --> 00:04:49,280
- Yeah?
- All right, pickles.

56
00:04:49,360 --> 00:04:50,360
Bring them.

57
00:04:58,920 --> 00:05:01,120
Alright, now, you wanna look good
in a swimsuit like me,

58
00:05:01,200 --> 00:05:03,720
come summertime, you'll want
a lot of this and lot of this.

59
00:05:03,800 --> 00:05:04,800
All right.

60
00:05:05,840 --> 00:05:06,840
Yeah.

61
00:05:08,640 --> 00:05:10,280
- You!
- Hey!

62
00:05:15,800 --> 00:05:16,800
Jim.

63
00:05:19,600 --> 00:05:22,480
Jim! Come on, it's lunchtime. Relax.

64
00:05:25,480 --> 00:05:26,920
It's lunchtime.

65
00:05:27,960 --> 00:05:30,800
No, Jim. We're on our... It's lunch!

66
00:05:31,880 --> 00:05:32,880
Oh, brother.

67
00:05:33,680 --> 00:05:38,000
Jim, you can't just pop up and jump
every time you hear a bell.

68
00:05:41,760 --> 00:05:43,600
G.C.P.D. Anybody here?

69
00:05:44,560 --> 00:05:46,040
Over, over here.

70
00:05:49,200 --> 00:05:50,240
You all right, sir? You okay?

71
00:05:51,440 --> 00:05:53,320
- Thank God you're here.
- Anybody dead?

72
00:05:54,160 --> 00:05:55,320
I don't think so.

73
00:05:55,400 --> 00:05:57,640
Some guy, he was stealing milk.

74
00:05:57,720 --> 00:06:00,640
I tried to stop him,
he hauls away my ATM machine.

75
00:06:01,560 --> 00:06:04,560
All right, nobody dead.
We're Homicide, and it's lunch.

76
00:06:04,640 --> 00:06:05,640
So have a good day, sir.

77
00:06:05,720 --> 00:06:07,560
Call 911 and someone
will take care of you.

78
00:06:07,640 --> 00:06:08,800
Wait a minute. Wait a minute.

79
00:06:08,880 --> 00:06:11,240
One guy did this?
Stole your ATM over milk?

80
00:06:11,320 --> 00:06:12,640
Little skinny ass dude.

81
00:06:12,720 --> 00:06:13,920
Guitar case.

82
00:06:14,000 --> 00:06:16,240
Drinking milk
like there's no more cows.

83
00:06:16,320 --> 00:06:18,560
"Don't vex me, mortal," he says.

84
00:06:18,640 --> 00:06:19,640
I'm sorry, what?

85
00:06:19,720 --> 00:06:22,440
Listen, if I had a dollar
for every hobo skeez

86
00:06:22,520 --> 00:06:26,080
that walks through that door thinks
they're God, I wouldn't be here.

87
00:06:26,160 --> 00:06:29,280
But this son of a bitch,
he wasn't fooling around.

88
00:06:29,360 --> 00:06:30,360
All right.

89
00:06:30,440 --> 00:06:32,880
You get a description of the vehicle,
license plate, something?

90
00:06:32,960 --> 00:06:34,760
He didn't have a vehicle.

91
00:06:34,840 --> 00:06:36,920
Then how'd he pull your ATM
from the wall?

92
00:06:37,000 --> 00:06:39,480
- How'd he take it away?
- That's what I'm telling you, man.

93
00:06:39,560 --> 00:06:41,720
He pulled it out of here
with his bare hands.

94
00:07:06,440 --> 00:07:07,440
I'm bored.

95
00:07:08,160 --> 00:07:10,040
{\an5}Poor little baby girl.

96
00:07:10,120 --> 00:07:12,200
{\an5}Cooped up in here all the time.

97
00:07:12,280 --> 00:07:15,280
{\an5}- You want some excitement.
- Yes, I do.

98
00:07:15,360 --> 00:07:16,760
{\an5}Can we just go somewhere?

99
00:07:18,160 --> 00:07:20,320
{\an5}How's that? Excited now?

100
00:07:20,400 --> 00:07:23,720
- What'd you do that for?
- Why are you here with me?

101
00:07:25,840 --> 00:07:28,360
{\an5}- I'm your secret weapon.
- Exactly.

102
00:07:29,160 --> 00:07:31,240
{\an5}But are you helping me help you?

103
00:07:31,880 --> 00:07:33,320
{\an5}No, you're not.

104
00:07:33,400 --> 00:07:35,200
You won't even learn the damn tune.

105
00:07:35,280 --> 00:07:38,400
{\an5}I told you this is important.

106
00:07:38,480 --> 00:07:41,160
{\an5}- I'm sorry, Mama.
- I'm not your mama.

107
00:07:41,960 --> 00:07:46,200
{\an5}Now, you might be my baby girl,
but I'm not your mama.

108
00:07:46,920 --> 00:07:47,920
Not yet.

109
00:07:48,920 --> 00:07:50,760
{\an5}You have to earn that.

110
00:07:55,680 --> 00:08:00,960
{\an5}(Foreign Language)

111
00:08:01,920 --> 00:08:09,160
{\an5}(Foreign Language)

112
00:08:14,240 --> 00:08:16,600
How is that even possible?

113
00:08:16,680 --> 00:08:17,800
Who is this guy?

114
00:08:17,880 --> 00:08:20,040
{\an5}No positive ID as of yet.

115
00:08:20,120 --> 00:08:21,280
{\an5}He's a street guy.

116
00:08:22,040 --> 00:08:24,400
{\an5}We think that this thing
has something to do

117
00:08:24,480 --> 00:08:27,360
{\an5}with his excessive <i>joie de vivre.</i>

118
00:08:27,440 --> 00:08:30,360
{\an5}Yeah, we found it in the suspect's
guitar case. It's some drug.

119
00:08:31,240 --> 00:08:32,440
{\an5}A drug did that?

120
00:08:33,400 --> 00:08:36,520
{\an5}- Wow.
- Nygma found traces of the drug.

121
00:08:36,600 --> 00:08:38,840
{\an5}He'll have a read on what the hell
this thing is by tomorrow morning.

122
00:08:38,920 --> 00:08:40,720
{\an5}Meantime, we'll try and ID
the strong man.

123
00:08:40,800 --> 00:08:41,800
{\an5}Yeah.

124
00:08:58,720 --> 00:09:00,720
I know your families are upset

125
00:09:01,280 --> 00:09:04,920
{\an5}but tell them everybody got
a piece of the Arkham project.

126
00:09:05,000 --> 00:09:06,720
It was a business decision.

127
00:09:06,800 --> 00:09:08,520
We didn't lose, Maroni didn't win.

128
00:09:08,600 --> 00:09:10,400
Maroni thinks he won.

129
00:09:10,480 --> 00:09:12,120
He thinks he won a great battle.

130
00:09:12,960 --> 00:09:14,880
- We need to hurt him.
- No.

131
00:09:14,960 --> 00:09:17,320
If we don't push back hard,
he's going to think...

132
00:09:17,400 --> 00:09:20,960
Nikolai, that fool will think
what I want him to think.

133
00:09:21,680 --> 00:09:23,440
No pushback, not yet.

134
00:09:23,520 --> 00:09:28,040
In my country, we say,
"Even a fool may bite the king,

135
00:09:29,000 --> 00:09:30,640
if he has teeth."

136
00:09:30,720 --> 00:09:32,840
Can the folklore, Niko.

137
00:09:32,920 --> 00:09:35,120
We're not in your godforsaken
country.

138
00:09:35,200 --> 00:09:37,680
We are here in Gotham
where we have plumbing,

139
00:09:37,760 --> 00:09:41,080
electricity, and Don Falcone
is the boss.

140
00:09:41,640 --> 00:09:45,280
He's playing that cluck Maroni
on a long line. Done.

141
00:09:45,360 --> 00:09:46,680
Why so angry, Fish?

142
00:09:47,480 --> 00:09:49,680
I speak my mind. Is no crime.

143
00:09:49,760 --> 00:09:54,480
And I assure you in my country,
we have all modern conveniences.

144
00:09:54,560 --> 00:09:56,080
Only difference, ladies.

145
00:09:56,160 --> 00:09:59,080
Ladies are in kitchen or in bed,
depending on their talents.

146
00:09:59,720 --> 00:10:02,160
I bet your mother was a lousy cook.

147
00:10:02,240 --> 00:10:04,880
- Don't speak of my mother.
- Or what?

148
00:10:07,480 --> 00:10:08,880
You're gonna hit a lady?

149
00:10:08,960 --> 00:10:10,120
That's enough.

150
00:10:10,200 --> 00:10:11,560
There'll be no bad blood here.

151
00:10:12,760 --> 00:10:14,520
My apologies, Don Falcone.

152
00:10:15,320 --> 00:10:16,320
We need each other.

153
00:10:17,400 --> 00:10:18,400
We're family.

154
00:10:28,960 --> 00:10:29,960
Hey.

155
00:10:31,880 --> 00:10:32,880
Excuse me.

156
00:10:33,440 --> 00:10:35,240
- You seen this guy by chance?
- No.

157
00:10:37,280 --> 00:10:38,280
Seen this guy?

158
00:10:39,280 --> 00:10:40,280
Excuse me.

159
00:10:42,560 --> 00:10:43,560
Familiar to you?

160
00:10:44,280 --> 00:10:45,480
Any chance you seen this guy?

161
00:10:46,680 --> 00:10:49,680
Yeah, I know him. It's Benny.

162
00:10:49,760 --> 00:10:51,120
He's a guitar player.

163
00:10:51,200 --> 00:10:52,440
Strung out like a string.

164
00:10:53,960 --> 00:10:56,480
- What'd he do?
- Nothing bad.

165
00:10:56,560 --> 00:10:58,840
He came into an inheritance
actually no one knew about.

166
00:10:58,920 --> 00:11:01,120
That's right. A million dollars.

167
00:11:01,200 --> 00:11:02,600
Farm, horses, real nice.

168
00:11:02,680 --> 00:11:03,720
You know where we can find him?

169
00:11:04,760 --> 00:11:05,760
20 dollars.

170
00:11:07,880 --> 00:11:08,880
Ten.

171
00:11:10,320 --> 00:11:11,400
Same as the bodega.

172
00:11:11,480 --> 00:11:13,280
Yeah, what's with
all the dairy products?

173
00:11:20,880 --> 00:11:23,920
Sir, G.C.P.D. Let me see those hands.

174
00:11:25,120 --> 00:11:26,120
Help me.

175
00:11:26,880 --> 00:11:29,120
I need more.

176
00:11:30,000 --> 00:11:31,600
More what? What'd you take?
What is it?

177
00:11:32,560 --> 00:11:33,920
It felt so good.

178
00:11:34,720 --> 00:11:37,560
And now I don't feel so good.
Something's wrong.

179
00:11:37,640 --> 00:11:39,960
I need more. Please.

180
00:11:40,040 --> 00:11:41,160
You have to find him.

181
00:11:41,760 --> 00:11:42,800
Find who?

182
00:11:42,880 --> 00:11:44,320
- The guy that gave you the stuff?
- Yeah.

183
00:11:44,400 --> 00:11:47,080
The man with a mangled ear.

184
00:11:47,160 --> 00:11:49,000
With a mangled ear. Go ahead.

185
00:11:49,080 --> 00:11:51,440
Stay calm, we got it.
We're gonna help.

186
00:11:51,520 --> 00:11:52,960
- Just put your...
- No, no, no.

187
00:11:53,040 --> 00:11:54,240
Hey, hey! Sir!

188
00:11:55,480 --> 00:11:57,040
Sir, we need you to calm down.

189
00:11:57,120 --> 00:11:59,120
- Calm down.
- Put your hands behind your back!

190
00:12:08,200 --> 00:12:10,640
- I said no.
- Put it down!

191
00:12:35,240 --> 00:12:36,240
What the hell?

192
00:12:38,240 --> 00:12:39,840
God help us if that drug gets out.

193
00:13:05,640 --> 00:13:06,880
Will you look at this shambles?

194
00:13:10,800 --> 00:13:11,960
What would your mother say?

195
00:13:14,560 --> 00:13:15,560
You know, I have half a mind

196
00:13:16,200 --> 00:13:19,240
to stick all this lot
straight into the bloody fire.

197
00:13:19,320 --> 00:13:21,640
- No fire.
- We'll see about that.

198
00:13:21,720 --> 00:13:22,720
Come on. Up you get.

199
00:13:24,160 --> 00:13:28,760
Wayne Enterprises is hosting
a charitable luncheon tomorrow.

200
00:13:28,840 --> 00:13:31,240
I took the liberty of accepting
their kind invitation

201
00:13:31,320 --> 00:13:33,200
- on your behalf, Master Bruce.
- Good.

202
00:13:34,760 --> 00:13:35,800
Is there breakfast?

203
00:13:36,600 --> 00:13:37,880
Yeah, I'll make you an egg.

204
00:13:39,240 --> 00:13:40,240
Does that mean you'll go?

205
00:13:41,320 --> 00:13:42,560
Yes.

206
00:13:42,640 --> 00:13:44,720
I have some questions I need
to ask the members of the board.

207
00:13:46,000 --> 00:13:48,520
- What kind of questions?
- About Arkham.

208
00:13:48,600 --> 00:13:51,120
It seems very likely those gangsters
were actually given their shares

209
00:13:51,200 --> 00:13:53,320
in Arkham by Wayne Enterprises.

210
00:13:53,400 --> 00:13:55,960
Well, that's how business is done,
isn't it?

211
00:13:56,840 --> 00:13:57,840
Is it?

212
00:14:00,840 --> 00:14:03,600
My parents didn't do business
that way, did they?

213
00:14:04,320 --> 00:14:05,640
No.

214
00:14:05,720 --> 00:14:06,720
No, they didn't, Master Bruce.

215
00:14:07,880 --> 00:14:08,920
The board might not know, of course.

216
00:14:09,000 --> 00:14:11,080
There's quite a bit of clever
camouflage used.

217
00:14:12,000 --> 00:14:14,200
Shell companies, offshore accounts
and so forth.

218
00:14:15,800 --> 00:14:19,840
Right. So, you learned all
of that from all of this, did you?

219
00:14:22,080 --> 00:14:23,320
Fantastic detective work.

220
00:14:23,960 --> 00:14:27,360
I still want to get the whole lot
and chuck it straight in the fire.

221
00:14:27,440 --> 00:14:29,200
Don't put anything in the fire,
Alfred.

222
00:14:31,000 --> 00:14:32,000
That's an order.

223
00:14:32,760 --> 00:14:33,920
Right, Master Bruce.

224
00:14:37,240 --> 00:14:38,240
Nothing in the fire.

225
00:14:46,280 --> 00:14:47,920
<i>We are live in downtown Gotham</i>

226
00:14:48,000 --> 00:14:50,880
<i>where a deadly new drug
has hit the streets.</i>

227
00:14:50,960 --> 00:14:54,200
<i>Nicknamed Viper,
users of this mystery drug</i>

228
00:14:54,280 --> 00:14:57,240
{\an5}<i>acquire great strength
and a euphoric sense of power,</i>

229
00:14:57,320 --> 00:14:59,440
{\an5}<i>but only for a few brief hours.</i>

230
00:14:59,520 --> 00:15:02,840
{\an5}<i>Then without exception,
they die a horrible death.</i>

231
00:15:09,200 --> 00:15:10,400
Let me out!

232
00:15:14,680 --> 00:15:15,680
Get off me!

233
00:15:18,760 --> 00:15:19,760
Let go of me!

234
00:15:25,120 --> 00:15:26,800
Get your crummy hands off me!

235
00:15:32,280 --> 00:15:34,160
It's really quite remarkable.

236
00:15:34,240 --> 00:15:37,480
Viper somehow activates unused DNA.

237
00:15:37,560 --> 00:15:40,480
The body starts to burn calcium
from the skeletal system as fuel,

238
00:15:41,240 --> 00:15:43,960
hence the victims' cravings
for milk and cheese.

239
00:15:44,040 --> 00:15:46,640
They're desperately trying
to replace the missing calcium,

240
00:15:47,360 --> 00:15:48,360
but they can't consume enough.

241
00:15:49,080 --> 00:15:53,440
Essentially their bones crumble,
then they suffocate and die.

242
00:15:53,520 --> 00:15:55,080
Have you seen anything
like this before?

243
00:15:55,160 --> 00:15:57,000
No, nobody has. Totally new.

244
00:15:57,080 --> 00:15:58,880
I can't tell you how thrilled I am
to be...

245
00:15:58,960 --> 00:16:00,800
No new reports for a few hours now.

246
00:16:00,880 --> 00:16:03,320
Maybe they're done.
Maybe they ran out of the stuff.

247
00:16:03,400 --> 00:16:04,400
I doubt it.

248
00:16:04,480 --> 00:16:07,480
Who would put this on the street?
Why?

249
00:16:07,560 --> 00:16:09,840
They're not even selling it,
they're giving it away.

250
00:16:09,920 --> 00:16:11,280
That's how you create demand.

251
00:16:11,360 --> 00:16:13,800
For a drug that kills you that fast?

252
00:16:13,880 --> 00:16:15,400
First, it makes you king
of the world.

253
00:16:15,480 --> 00:16:16,560
There'll be takers.

254
00:16:16,640 --> 00:16:18,000
There'll be mayhem that's for sure.

255
00:16:18,080 --> 00:16:19,480
But it's skell-on-skell mayhem.

256
00:16:19,560 --> 00:16:22,120
If we keep the decent citizens
indoors for a couple of weeks,

257
00:16:22,200 --> 00:16:23,320
let the scumbags have at it?

258
00:16:23,400 --> 00:16:25,360
Voilà, the end of crime.

259
00:16:25,440 --> 00:16:27,720
Yeah, that's a nice thought, but no.

260
00:16:28,440 --> 00:16:29,840
This stuff seems hard to make, no?

261
00:16:30,640 --> 00:16:32,720
It takes a high level
of technical sophistication.

262
00:16:32,800 --> 00:16:34,520
A state-of-the-art lab
made this stuff.

263
00:16:34,600 --> 00:16:37,160
Okay, so who has the biggest
and best lab in the city?

264
00:16:37,240 --> 00:16:39,120
The best is WellZyn.

265
00:16:39,200 --> 00:16:40,480
