515
00:28:52,720 --> 00:28:55,120
I was just on my way
to an appointment,

516
00:28:55,200 --> 00:28:57,320
but yes, I know Stan Potolsky.

517
00:28:57,960 --> 00:28:59,240
He was a student of mine.

518
00:29:00,040 --> 00:29:01,480
A very brilliant student.

519
00:29:02,160 --> 00:29:04,120
And you've stayed
in touch over the years.

520
00:29:04,200 --> 00:29:09,240
We have. He may be a biochemist,
but philosophy is a passion of his.

521
00:29:09,320 --> 00:29:11,360
What can you tell us
about WellZyn firing him?

522
00:29:11,440 --> 00:29:16,520
Research for WellZyn led him
into some dark moral corners.

523
00:29:16,600 --> 00:29:18,040
WellZyn said he made shampoo.

524
00:29:18,120 --> 00:29:19,840
Where are the dark moral corners
in that?

525
00:29:19,920 --> 00:29:20,920
Shampoo?

526
00:29:22,040 --> 00:29:23,560
They say that, do they?

527
00:29:24,480 --> 00:29:28,160
No, no, Stan designed
pharmaceutical weapons

528
00:29:28,240 --> 00:29:30,280
to be used by combat troops.

529
00:29:30,360 --> 00:29:33,040
Drugs that worked
on an epigenetic level.

530
00:29:33,120 --> 00:29:34,240
Imagine an army

531
00:29:34,320 --> 00:29:37,800
made up of soldiers so strong
that they can tear a man apart

532
00:29:37,880 --> 00:29:39,400
with their bare hands.

533
00:29:39,480 --> 00:29:42,320
Of course, at the beginning,
there were side effects.

534
00:29:42,400 --> 00:29:43,560
Yeah, death.

535
00:29:43,640 --> 00:29:45,160
But Viper was the first batch.

536
00:29:45,240 --> 00:29:47,840
They worked out the kinks
in the second version.

537
00:29:47,920 --> 00:29:49,240
Called it Venom.

538
00:29:51,720 --> 00:29:55,400
By then, Stan had acquired
some clarity.

539
00:29:57,480 --> 00:30:00,440
He appealed to his
bosses to end the program.

540
00:30:01,040 --> 00:30:04,080
They refused,
so he went over their heads

541
00:30:04,160 --> 00:30:05,640
to Thomas and Martha Wayne.

542
00:30:07,360 --> 00:30:09,520
He convinced them to shut it down.

543
00:30:09,600 --> 00:30:13,800
And when they died, WellZyn
immediately revived the program

544
00:30:13,880 --> 00:30:16,360
with the blessings
of Wayne Enterprises.

545
00:30:16,440 --> 00:30:18,200
In the end, there was nothing
for Stan to do

546
00:30:18,280 --> 00:30:21,200
but to resort
to more radical measures.

547
00:30:21,280 --> 00:30:22,600
Killing people.

548
00:30:22,680 --> 00:30:25,400
I'm not hearing a sense
of moral outrage, Professor.

549
00:30:25,480 --> 00:30:28,240
If you don't mind,
I'll reserve my moral outrage

550
00:30:28,320 --> 00:30:30,200
for the true villains of this piece.

551
00:30:30,280 --> 00:30:31,280
You mean WellZyn.

552
00:30:32,840 --> 00:30:34,520
You planned this with Potolsky.

553
00:30:35,520 --> 00:30:36,920
- Yes.
- Where is he?

554
00:30:37,000 --> 00:30:38,080
Talk fast, bub!

555
00:30:38,160 --> 00:30:40,880
Oh, what are you gonna do to me?
I'm an old man! I'm dying.

556
00:30:40,960 --> 00:30:43,080
I'll help you die quicker,
you terrorist.

557
00:30:43,160 --> 00:30:46,680
Soon, Stan will issue a statement
the world won't be able to ignore.

558
00:30:46,760 --> 00:30:47,800
Soon?

559
00:30:47,880 --> 00:30:49,400
- Today?
- You're already too late.

560
00:30:49,480 --> 00:30:50,840
Now, you tell us where he is
right now.

561
00:30:50,920 --> 00:30:53,040
Wait a minute! You said
you had an appointment, right?

562
00:30:53,120 --> 00:30:54,160
Where were you going?

563
00:30:54,240 --> 00:30:57,440
Bravo!
You've asked the right question.

564
00:30:57,520 --> 00:30:59,160
The first step to enlightenment.

565
00:31:21,600 --> 00:31:24,200
- Where is he? Where's Potolsky?
- Those hypocrites.

566
00:31:24,280 --> 00:31:26,960
Empty altruism will not erase
what they've done.

567
00:31:28,120 --> 00:31:29,120
They must pay.

568
00:31:29,200 --> 00:31:31,640
- Who? Who must pay?
- WellZyn.

569
00:31:31,720 --> 00:31:33,280
Wayne Enterprises.

570
00:31:33,880 --> 00:31:37,400
Everyone will finally
see them for what they are.

571
00:31:37,480 --> 00:31:39,360
How? Where's Potolsky headed?

572
00:31:40,720 --> 00:31:42,080
What's altruism?

573
00:31:44,720 --> 00:31:45,720
Charity.

574
00:31:48,720 --> 00:31:49,720
I know where he's going.

575
00:31:54,080 --> 00:31:56,960
- Name, please?
- He's, Bruce Wayne.

576
00:31:57,040 --> 00:31:58,040
Master Bruce Wayne.

577
00:31:58,120 --> 00:31:59,440
- Just this way. Thank you.
- Thank you.

578
00:32:33,560 --> 00:32:37,240
<i>Wayne Enterprises
is a helping hand...</i>

579
00:32:38,080 --> 00:32:39,280
<i>A port in the storm.</i>

580
00:32:40,240 --> 00:32:41,720
Oh, that's Ms. Mathis.

581
00:32:41,800 --> 00:32:43,760
She worked closely with your father.

582
00:32:43,840 --> 00:32:46,800
<i>Wayne Enterprises
is a shelter for all.</i>

583
00:32:47,760 --> 00:32:48,880
<i>And clean water...</i>

584
00:33:08,880 --> 00:33:10,200
Please, sit, Bruce.

585
00:33:12,080 --> 00:33:14,160
It is so good to see you out
and about.

586
00:33:14,840 --> 00:33:15,880
Glad to be here.

587
00:33:15,960 --> 00:33:20,000
All of us at Wayne Enterprises
are so sorry for your loss.

588
00:33:22,240 --> 00:33:23,680
So, are all you here on the board?

589
00:33:24,440 --> 00:33:28,000
Oh, heavens no.
We're middle management.

590
00:33:28,080 --> 00:33:30,280
The board members
don't do this sort of thing.

591
00:33:31,000 --> 00:33:32,000
No?

592
00:33:32,960 --> 00:33:33,960
Why not?

593
00:33:34,800 --> 00:33:38,240
Well, they're very busy people,
Bruce.

594
00:33:39,040 --> 00:33:40,640
Your family created a company

595
00:33:40,720 --> 00:33:44,040
worth billions
and billions of dollars.

596
00:33:44,120 --> 00:33:46,400
- How awesome is that?
- Awesome.

597
00:33:47,360 --> 00:33:49,080
I wanted to speak to them
because I've found

598
00:33:49,160 --> 00:33:50,760
what looks like serious
irregularities

599
00:33:50,840 --> 00:33:51,840
in the Arkham project.

600
00:33:52,640 --> 00:33:53,640
Irregularities?

601
00:34:03,120 --> 00:34:06,840
I can assure you, Bruce,
that Wayne Enterprises

602
00:34:06,920 --> 00:34:09,840
would never countenance
doing business with criminals.

603
00:34:09,920 --> 00:34:11,600
- Just wouldn't happen.
- I hope so,

604
00:34:11,680 --> 00:34:13,760
but I'd like to speak
directly with the board myself.

605
00:34:15,080 --> 00:34:16,080
Can you make that happen?

606
00:34:17,800 --> 00:34:19,040
I can certainly try.

607
00:34:23,040 --> 00:34:25,200
They prefer to communicate
with minors

608
00:34:25,280 --> 00:34:27,560
via the usual legal mediation, but...

609
00:34:27,640 --> 00:34:28,960
<i>Good evening, ladies and gentleman.</i>

610
00:34:29,040 --> 00:34:32,880
<i>This is a public service announcement
on behalf of all living creatures.</i>

611
00:34:33,640 --> 00:34:36,000
<i>You've heard of a drug called Viper?</i>

612
00:34:39,280 --> 00:34:40,280
<i>That's me.</i>

613
00:34:41,400 --> 00:34:46,280
<i>I made it for WellZyn,
a subsidiary of Wayne Enterprises.</i>

614
00:34:46,360 --> 00:34:48,720
- Is this true?
- Of course not, Bruce.

615
00:34:48,800 --> 00:34:50,840
I mean, this man is clearly insane.

616
00:35:00,400 --> 00:35:01,920
The AC plant, where is it?
On the roof?

617
00:35:02,000 --> 00:35:03,480
Straight ahead, staircase
across the ballroom.

618
00:35:03,560 --> 00:35:04,720
Clear the ballroom!

619
00:35:04,800 --> 00:35:08,880
<i>I hoped that a demonstration
using street people would suffice,</i>

620
00:35:08,960 --> 00:35:11,840
<i>but seems bad things
only truly happen</i>

621
00:35:11,920 --> 00:35:13,920
<i>when they happen to important people.</i>

622
00:35:15,680 --> 00:35:16,680
<i>Like you!</i>

623
00:35:22,640 --> 00:35:24,720
G.C.P.D.! Everybody out!

624
00:35:24,800 --> 00:35:25,800
Now!

625
00:35:29,400 --> 00:35:30,400
Turn it off!

626
00:35:32,520 --> 00:35:33,520
Can't do that.

627
00:35:34,240 --> 00:35:35,960
Turn it off or I'll shoot!

628
00:35:36,040 --> 00:35:37,040
Go ahead.

629
00:35:37,640 --> 00:35:38,720
My work is done.

630
00:35:54,760 --> 00:35:56,080
Turn around!
Put your hands behind your head!

631
00:35:56,160 --> 00:35:57,760
Interlock your fingers!

632
00:35:57,840 --> 00:35:58,840
That's all right.

633
00:35:59,600 --> 00:36:02,880
You're angry and confused.
I understand.

634
00:36:04,240 --> 00:36:06,480
There's no more need for violence.

635
00:36:07,440 --> 00:36:08,440
Don't shoot!

636
00:36:09,600 --> 00:36:11,240
That's considerate of you.

637
00:36:13,800 --> 00:36:14,960
I'm leaving now.

638
00:36:17,120 --> 00:36:19,280
Go look in warehouse 39.

639
00:36:19,360 --> 00:36:20,640
You're not going anywhere!

640
00:36:20,720 --> 00:36:23,240
I can go anywhere I want!

641
00:36:26,640 --> 00:36:27,640
Don't do it!

642
00:36:36,200 --> 00:36:38,240
You really can have
too much of a good thing.

643
00:37:16,080 --> 00:37:17,080
Nothing.

644
00:37:18,880 --> 00:37:19,880
What'd you expect?

645
00:37:20,640 --> 00:37:21,640
It's Gotham.

646
00:37:32,080 --> 00:37:33,440
It's Mathis.

647
00:37:33,520 --> 00:37:35,040
I'm outside the site. They're here.

648
00:37:36,560 --> 00:37:38,560
No. I think we should leave them be.

649
00:37:39,200 --> 00:37:40,280
There's nothing here for them.

650
00:37:42,120 --> 00:37:44,520
We'll review that if they get close.

651
00:38:31,520 --> 00:38:32,640
It's been ten minutes.

652
00:38:32,720 --> 00:38:35,320
I, I assure you,
my friend is reliable.

653
00:38:37,760 --> 00:38:38,800
You scared, Penguin?

654
00:38:39,880 --> 00:38:41,520
Your voice is doing that shaky thing.

655
00:38:43,040 --> 00:38:45,000
No, sir. I'm fine.

656
00:38:45,720 --> 00:38:46,720
You don't have to act tough.

657
00:38:47,520 --> 00:38:48,800
Nerves are a good thing.

658
00:38:48,880 --> 00:38:52,200
Perhaps I am a bit jittery, sir.

659
00:38:52,280 --> 00:38:53,680
Good.

660
00:38:53,760 --> 00:38:54,760
You should be.

661
00:38:55,720 --> 00:38:58,680
Because if my boys don't make it,
neither do you.

662
00:39:06,320 --> 00:39:07,400
Got them!

663
00:39:07,480 --> 00:39:08,480
Keep going!

664
00:39:10,840 --> 00:39:13,560
Take that, Falcone,
you son of a bitch!

665
00:39:13,640 --> 00:39:16,480
Huh? I told you, Frankie,
the kid's a player.

666
00:39:16,560 --> 00:39:17,560
He's got a future.

667
00:39:18,640 --> 00:39:20,040
What are you waiting
here like an old lady?

668
00:39:21,080 --> 00:39:22,080
Go!

669
00:39:30,680 --> 00:39:31,680
Untie me.

670
00:39:34,760 --> 00:39:36,640
Say "pretty please."

671
00:39:38,800 --> 00:39:39,800
Please.

672
00:39:47,480 --> 00:39:50,640
Sometimes I think
you really don't like me.

673
00:39:51,920 --> 00:39:55,360
Now, would I be backing your takeover
if I didn't like you?

674
00:39:56,680 --> 00:39:57,800
And that stuff with Falcone,

675
00:39:57,880 --> 00:39:59,840
well, we have to look good
for the old man.

676
00:39:59,920 --> 00:40:01,960
If he figures out
we're working together...

677
00:40:03,920 --> 00:40:05,000
we'd be cooked.

678
00:40:05,880 --> 00:40:08,960
- Patience.
- I have no more patience.

679
00:40:09,760 --> 00:40:11,000
The old man has to go.

680
00:40:12,280 --> 00:40:13,720
We must strike soon.

681
00:40:16,120 --> 00:40:19,600
Yes. But softly.

682
00:41:05,960 --> 00:41:06,960
Excuse me.

683
00:41:08,520 --> 00:41:11,000
I couldn't help but overhear
that aria you were humming.

684
00:41:11,720 --> 00:41:14,160
- Oh, yes. It's my favorite.
- Mine, too.

685
00:41:15,640 --> 00:41:17,720
Oh, well, there you go.

686
00:41:18,920 --> 00:41:20,920
I'm sorry, I, I just...

687
00:41:21,000 --> 00:41:22,680
I, I didn't mean to bother you.

688
00:41:24,200 --> 00:41:26,040
My mother sang that to me
when I was young.

689
00:41:26,800 --> 00:41:28,520
Her whole life, she sang that to me.

690
00:41:29,640 --> 00:41:31,040
I hadn't heard it in a while,
and I...

691
00:41:32,080 --> 00:41:33,440
I had to smile because you look...

692
00:41:36,720 --> 00:41:39,280
Anyhow, sorry, I'm rambling on.

693
00:41:40,080 --> 00:41:41,280
No, that's okay.

694
00:41:42,560 --> 00:41:43,560
Do you want to listen?

695
00:41:45,520 --> 00:41:48,880
- Well, yeah. Sure, thank you.
- Let's sit down.

